  //     "Dental Veneers are undoubtedly the best way for modern dentistry to mimic nature. Cosmetic dentistry has always sought to imitate nature rather than improve it. Porcelain veneers aren&#8217;t the only way to change a person&#8217;s smile, but they&#8217;re a popular choice for patients who want a lot of control over their appearance (change color, size, [&hellip;]",
  //   author: "Dr. Tiziana Procopio",
  //   content:
  //     '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dental Veneers are undoubtedly the best way for modern dentistry to mimic nature. Cosmetic dentistry has always sought to imitate nature rather than improve it. Porcelain veneers aren\'t the only way to change a person\'s smile, but they\'re a popular choice for patients who want a lot of control over their appearance (change color, size, shape, etc.). Veneers are a quick way to improve the appearance of your teeth and are ideal for people who have stained, chipped, or gapped teeth. On the other hand, Veneers are a long-term solution, and having them placed is a significant investment. Before you and your dentist decide whether veneers are right for you, you should educate yourself on everything you can about them, including how much they cost and how to care for them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"align":"right","id":4651,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="alignright size-full"><img src="https://pwdds.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/vig-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-4651"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A veneer is a tooth-colored, wafer-thin shell that covers the front surface of teeth to improve appearance while providing strength and resilience like natural tooth enamel. During in-office procedures, they are customized to the shape of your teeth and bonded to the tooth\'s original enamel. Porcelain or resin composite materials are used to create dental veneers. We\'ll go over the distinctions between the two in more detail below.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->\n<h4>Why Do Dentists Recommend Dental Veneers?</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Veneers are a more discrete option than crowns or braces. They can be used to fill in gaps and fix minor alignment issues. Veneers are also used as a cosmetic solution to brighten and straighten teeth and correct issues like discoloration, fractures, and chips.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->\n<h4>What Is the Difference Between Porcelain And Composite Veneers?</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"align":"right","id":4655,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="alignright size-full"><img src="https://pwdds.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/vig-3.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-4655"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The most common veneer materials are traditional porcelain veneers and composite resin veneers. Porcelain veneers are the best option for correcting shape and color issues, and they have a lifespan of 10 to 20 years. Porcelain veneers are typically half the price of composite veneers. In most cases, composites can be created while you wait, allowing for same-day treatment. Instead of being shaped and sculpted in a separate lab, they are shaped and carved on your teeth. Another benefit of composite veneers is their reversibility. Porcelain veneers require the reshaping of your natural teeth to accommodate the veneer. Composites require only minor prep work on your natural teeth, which means they are not permanently altered to the point where the composite material cannot be removed and replaced as needed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->\n<h4>Porcelain vs. Resin Veneers: What\'s the Difference?</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As previously stated, porcelain veneers have several advantages, but you may also be familiar with resin composite veneers. Either of these materials is used to make them. Consult your dentist to find out which material is best for you.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The resin composite option is customized to your smile and designed to appear natural. This material is also highly durable, and with proper maintenance, it can last for several years. The most significant disadvantage of resin composite is that it is not stain-resistant, which means it will darken over time, just like natural teeth.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href="tel:925-933-5677">Contact</a>&nbsp;your Walnut Creek Dentist, Dr. Tiziana Procopio Towle, DDS at&nbsp;<a href="https://pwdds.com/">Procopio Towle Dental Office</a>&nbsp;today to learn more about Dental Veneers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->\n<h4>Resource: </h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href="https://pwdds.com/the-step-by-step-guide-to-dentures/">The step-by-step guide to dentures.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>*Neither this nor any other content in this media is meant to prescribe, recommend, or prevent any treatment or procedure. We highly recommend that you get the advice of a qualified dentist or other medical practitioners regarding your specific dental condition</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->',
